Question 1 Section 1

Figure 1 is the histogram of sales differences of stores in percentage. I fit the percentage of sales differences between period 1 (before the trial) and period 2 (after the trial) with a linear regression model. The sales difference of stores in trial is 1.42% 95% CI[0.85% 1.98%]. The sales difference of stores not in trial is 0.1% 95% CI[-0.45% 0.65%]. The new store layout increased 1.31% 95% CI[0.53%, 2.1%] of sales difference of stores. This improvement is significant, \(t(538) = 3.27\), \(p = 0.0011\).

Figure 1. A histogram of the sales difference of stores. New design stores and ordinary stores are specified by different colours.

Moreover, I prefer using percentage data to GBP data while practicing ANOVA to examine the effect of the new layout. While sales of some of stores are generally much higher than sales of the others, examining the difference of sales is insufficient. For example, the store, whose Outlet_ID is EhJV, has a fewer sales improvement in GBP than the store JI92. Nonetheless, the original sales of the store EhJV is much lower than that of the store JI92. Actually, this store performs better as it has a higher increasing rate, \(8.46%\). Therefore, I prefer percentage measure while performing ANOVA. On the other hand, I also performed repeated measure ANOVA to correctly control the link between sales_1 and sales2 since sales1 and sales2 are not independent. In this case, sales differences are not needed, so I can simply use the GBP data to examine the effect of the new store design.

Question 2 Section 1

Figure 2 presents the sales difference in percentage by different outlet types. There is a strong interaction between intrial and outlettype, \(F(2, 534) = 57.08\). That means a different effect in different outlet types exists. For community_convenience outlets, stores in trial got 3.49% 95% CI[2.56% 4.43%] of sales improvement more than stores without any change, \(t(534) = 7.33\), \(p < 0.0001\). For superstores, stores with the new layout got 3.48% 95% CI[2% 4.96%] of sales improvement more than stores not in trial, \(t(534) = 4.625\), \(p < 0.0001\). However, the pattern at city_centre_convenience outlets is different. The percentage of sales difference of stores in trial is 4.39% 95% CI[-5.61% -3.18%] lower than that of stores not in trial, \(t(534) = -7.11\), \(p < 0.0001\). Therefore, the new store design will not cause a positive effect to the sales of city_centre_convenience outlets.

Figure 2. A scatter plot of the sales difference in percentage by different types of outlets. New design stores and ordinary stores are specified by different colours.

Figure 3 shows the relationship between sales difference in percentage and staff turnover rate. It seems that the correlation between these two variables is not significant as those two lines vary without any pattern. Actually, staff_turnover is not a significant predictor of sales difference in the model, \(F(1, 537) = 0.1289\), \(p = 0.7197\).

Figure 3. A scatter plot of sales difference by staff turnover rate. New design stores and ordinary stores are specified by different colours.

## [1] "community_convenience"   "city_centre_convenience" "superstore"
# Create a data frame "sales.short" with correct data structures
sales.short = sales %>%
  mutate(outlettype = factor(outlettype, levels = c("community_convenience", "city_centre_convenience", "superstore")),
         sales_change_GBP = sales_2 - sales_1,
         sales_change_percentage = ((sales_2 - sales_1) / sales_1) * 100,
         intrial = factor(intrial, levels = c(TRUE, FALSE), labels = c("In Trial", "Not In Trial")))
view(sales.short)

# Create a data frame "sales.summary" to store the statistical data
sales.summary = sales.short %>%
  group_by(intrial) %>%
  summarise(n = n(),
            mean.GBP = mean(sales_change_GBP), 
            mean.percentage = mean(sales_change_percentage),
            standard.deviation.GBP = sd(sales_change_GBP),
            standard.deviation.percentage = sd(sales_change_percentage))
view(sales.summary)

Controlling the link between sales_1 and sales_2

Create a longer dataset

# Create a longer dataset to gather the variable "sales_1" and the variable "sales_2"
sales.long = pivot_longer(sales, c(sales_1, sales_2), 
                          names_to = "Period", 
                          values_to = "Sales", 
                          names_transform = list(Period = factor, 
                                                 Sales = as.numeric), 
                          names_prefix = "sales_") %>%
  mutate(outlettype = factor(outlettype, levels = c("community_convenience", "city_centre_convenience", "superstore")),
         intrial = factor(intrial, levels = c(TRUE, FALSE), labels = c("In Trial", "Not In Trial")))
view(sales.long)

Model3: Repeated Measure ANOVA

contrasts(sales.long$Period) = contr.sum
# Repeated Measure ANOVA
m.sales.period = aov(Sales~Period*intrial + Error(Outlet_ID/Period), 
                             data = sales.long)
# Check the outcome of the model "m.sales.period"
summary(m.sales.period)

The sales difference for stores in trial is 408804 GBP 95% CI[269755, 547853] higher than the sale difference for stores not in trial, \(t(538) = 5.775\), \(p-value < 0.0001\).
